{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 13:00:00.795983", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nNetwork overview\n- Topology: host_1 — switch_1 — switch_2 — host_2, with inter-switch link on eth1.\n- Function: P4 bmv2 dataplane with a bloom filter program; IPv4 LPM table for forwarding.\n\n1) Anomaly detection\n- End-to-end reachability is broken in both directions:\n  - host_1 -> host_2 ping: timeout\n  - host_2 -> host_1 ping: timeout\n- get_reachability: status unknown for both host pairs (no successful ICMP).\n\n2) Localization of the faulty device(s)\n- Hosts are properly configured and generating traffic:\n  - host_1: 10.0.0.1/24 on eth0; ARP entry for 10.0.0.2 → 00:00:0a:00:00:02 (PERMANENT)\n  - host_2: 10.0.0.2/24 on eth0; ARP entry for 10.0.0.1 → 00:00:0a:00:00:01 (PERMANENT)\n  - Both hosts show TX packets (6) and RX 0, consistent with attempts to ping and not receiving replies.\n\n- Switch interface counters indicate traffic reaches switch_1 but is not forwarded:\n  - switch_2:\n    - eth0 (to host_2): RX 6, TX 0 (receiving host_2 traffic)\n    - eth1 (to switch_1): TX 6, RX 0 (forwarding toward switch_1)\n  - switch_1:\n    - eth1 (from switch_2): RX 6, TX 0 (receiving from switch_2)\n    - eth0 (from host_1): RX 6, TX 0 (receiving from host_1)\n  - Key observation: switch_1 transmits 0 packets on both ports, despite receiving packets on both. This localizes the drop to switch_1’s dataplane.\n\n- bmv2 runtime behavior/logs:\n  - switch_2 logs show normal pipeline behavior when processing ICMP/IPv4:\n    - Parser extracts ethernet/ipv4, applies MyIngress.ipv4_lpm, hits LPM entries for 10.0.0.1, sets egress_spec=2, and transmits out port 2 (inter-switch link).\n  - switch_1 log shows startup and table programming lines, but no runtime packet-processing logs were observed; TX counters remain at 0 on both interfaces.\n\n- Control-plane access inconsistency:\n  - switch_2: able to list table structure.\n  - switch_1: simple_switch_CLI connection failed (“Could not connect to thrift client on port 9090”), even though switch_1’s log indicates Thrift started. This indicates a potential control-plane issue specific to switch_1.\n\nConclusion on localization: The fault is at switch_1. It receives traffic on both interfaces but forwards none, causing blackholing of packets in both directions.\n\n3) Likely root cause\n- Misbehavior of switch_1’s P4 pipeline or table state leading to packet drops:\n  - Although switch_1’s startup log shows IPv4 LPM entries for 10.0.0.1 → port 1 and 10.0.0.2 → port 2 and default action set to drop, the lack of any TX and absence of runtime forwarding logs suggest packets are not reaching (or not matching) the forwarding stage, or a drop action is triggered earlier (e.g., a bloom-filter-related drop or a default drop path).\n  - The inability to connect via Thrift CLI to switch_1, contrasted with switch_2 working, further suggests a control-plane or instance mismatch on switch_1 that may have resulted in incorrect/absent table programming at runtime, despite the startup log lines.\n\nEvidence summary\n- Reachability: Both directions fail (timeouts).\n- Hosts: Correct IP/ARP, TX observed, no RX.\n- Switch_2:\n  - For host_2→host_1, LPM table hit and TX on inter-switch link observed in logs; counters reflect TX on eth1.\n- Switch_1:\n  - RX on both ports, TX on neither port; no runtime TX logs; CLI connectivity issue.\n- Inter-switch link: Operational (switch_2 eth1 TX matches switch_1 eth1 RX).\n\nAssessment of network health\n- Current state: Unhealthy. End-to-end connectivity is broken.\n- Fault domain: switch_1 dataplane/control-plane.\n- Root cause hypothesis: switch_1’s pipeline is dropping all packets due to misconfiguration or inconsistent runtime table state (potentially bloom filter stage or default drop path), compounded by control-plane access issues preventing verification/repair of LPM entries on switch_1.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null},